  "prompt": "Do anti-money laundering regulations exist?",
  "response": "Yes, anti-money laundering (AML) regulations exist in many countries and at international levels. These regulations are designed to prevent criminals from disguising illegally obtained money as legitimate income. Key aspects include:\n\n1. Requirements for financial institutions to:\n- Verify customer identities\n- Report suspicious transactions\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Implement compliance programs\n\n2. Major regulatory frameworks in different regions:\n- United States: Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- European Union: Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n- International: Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n\n3. Regulated industries include:\n- Banks\n- Credit unions\n- Investment firms\n- Money transfer services\n- Casinos\n- Real estate companies\n\n4. Consequences for non-compliance can include:\n- Significant financial penalties\n- Criminal prosecution\n- Loss of business licenses\n\nThese regulations aim to detect and prevent financial crimes like money laundering, terrorist financing, and other illicit financial activities.",
